ibalism sought to territorialize their distinctive societies. He demonstrates that cultural conflict on the frontier was a defining characteristic of Brazil's transition from colony to independent nation and a fundamental consequence of its relationship to a wider world. The study moves Brazil to a prominent place in our understanding of the hemispheric sweep of internal colonization in the Americas. Essays based on material in this book have won the 2006 CLAH Prize and the 2005 Tibesar Prize.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362527340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503625273423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503625273/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles